\begin_layout Section
The parallel interface card
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parallel interface card is very simple to pilot.
 It is plugged to the computer with a parallel cable and it allows to master
 eight channels (with relays) corresponding to the eight bits of a byte.
 Thus, sending one byte to the card through the parallel cable instruct
 to open (bit is 1) or close (bit is 0) respective channels.
 The 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:Pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
econum
\end_layout

\end_inset

 package contains functions to pilot that card through a special LPT driver
 under Tcl/Tk.
 This driver is only working under Windows 95 -> XP.
 The card must be connected to usual LPT1, LPT2, or LPT3 parallel ports
 (no exotic parallel ports supported yet).
 It use is very simple through the unique 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:Code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
para()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 function.
 Basically, you specify a vector of eight logicals inducating the state
 of each channel you want, the parallel port where the card is connected
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is much more convenient to use the 
\begin_inset Flex Code
